{"cursor":"54299","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox Hindu leader | |name = Adi Shankaracharya |image = Raja Ravi Varma -\nSankaracharya.jpg |caption = Adi Shankara with Disciples, by Raja Ravi Varma\n(1904) |birth_date = 788 CE |birth_place= Kaladi, Chera Kingdom present\nday Kerala, India |birth_name = Shankara |death_date = 820 CE |death_place =\nKedarnath, Pala Empire present day Uttarakhand, India |guru = Govinda\nBhagavatpada |philosophy = Advaita Vedanta |honours = Expounded Advaita\nVedanta, Hindu Revivalism, Founded Dashanami Sampradaya, Shanmata |quote =\n|footnotes = }}\n\n\n'Adi Shankara' (early 8th century CE Earlier generations of scholars proposed\n788â820 CE. Other proposals are 686â718 CE, 44 BCE, or as\nearly as 509â477 BCE. }}), pronounced , also known as\n'{{IAST|Ädi Åaá¹karÄcÄri}}', '{{IAST|Åaá¹karÄcÄrya}}', '{{IAST|Åaá¹kara\nBhagavatpÄda}}', '{{IAST|Åaá¹kara BhagavatpÄdÄcÄrya}}' and '{{IAST|Ädi\nÅaá¹karÄcÄrya}}' was a Hindu philosopher from Kaladi in present day Eranakulam\ndistrict, Kerala, India who consolidated the doctrine of [[advaita\nvedanta|advaita vedÄnta]]. [http://books.google-\n.co.in/books?id=lsJbVICEOTcC&pg=PA13&dq=Adi+Shankara&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Es90T7a9NIy3-\nrAeE3_HmCg&ved=0CFAQuwUwBg#v=onepage&q=Adi%20Shankara&f=false The Seven\nSpiritual Laws Of Yoga], Deepak Chopra, John Wiley & Sons, 2006, ISBN 81-265-0696-\n2, ISBN 978-81-265-0696-5\n\nHis works in Sanskrit establish the doctrine of [[advaita]], the unity of the\n[[Ätman (Hinduism)|Ätman]] and [[nirguna brahman]], brahman without\nattributes. [http://www.sringeri.net/history/sri-adi-\nshankaracharya Sri Adi Shankaracharya], Sringeri Sharada Peetham, India\nHis works elaborate on ideas found in the [[Upanishads]]. He wrote copious\ncommentaries on the Vedic canon ([[Brahma Sutra]], principal upanishads and\n[[Bhagavad Gita]]) in support of his thesis.\n\nThe main opponent in his work is the Mimamsa school of thought, though he also\noffers arguments against the views of some other schools like Samkhya and\ncertain schools of Buddhism. [http://www.sringeri.net/history/sri-adi-\nshankaracharya/biography Biography of Sri Adi Shankaracharya], Sringeri Sharada\nPeetham, India [http://books.google.co.in/books-\n?ei=09d0T6ygK4PTrQf5l4SgDQ&id=IPasbJW-\n1PwC&dq=inauthor%3A%22Shyama+Kumar+Chattopadhyaya%22&q=Mimamsa#v=snippet&q=Mima-\nmsa&f=false The philosophy of Sankar's Advaita Vedanta], Shyama Kumar\nChattopadhyaya, Sarup & Sons, 2000, ISBN 81-7625-222-0, ISBN 978-81-7625-222-\n5\n\nShankara travelled across the Indian subcontinent to propagate his philosophy\nthrough discourses and debates with other thinkers. He established the\nimportance of monastic life as sanctioned in the Upanishads and Brahma Sutra,\nin a time when the Mimamsa school established strict ritualism and ridiculed\nmonasticism. He is reputed to have founded four [[#Mathas|mathas]]\n(\"monasteries\"), which helped in the historical development, revival and\nspread of Advaita Vedanta of which he is known as the greatest\nrevivalist. Adi Shankara is believed to be\nthe organiser of the Dashanami monastic order and the founder of the Shanmata\ntradition of worship.\n","linknr":1076,"url":"Adi_Shankara","recorded":1374963500,"links":["//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scri